Data Visualization¶

Stats 141B¶

Lecture 15¶

Chloropleth map

  • Could just report a stat, "the average cost of daycare in 2014 was 13,300 USD"
  • Instead allows you to ask questions, "what is the average cost of childcare where I live?"
  • Could contain implicit distortions of the data, chloropleth map suggests that larger geographic areas have higher weight

Data Visualization¶

Old way¶

  • Named plots:

    • histogram, scatterplot, time series plot, etc.

  • Increasingly complicated named plots (e.g. Hexbin plot with marginal distributions)

  • Lacks versitility: many options as you build a plot, a named plot can only give you so many options

New way¶

  • Deconstructing the plot: understand and name the components
  • Grammar of graphics: rules that guide how these fit together

Data Visualization: Python landscape¶

Low level drawing¶

  • Matplotlib

Named plots¶

  • Pyplot
  • Seaborn
  • Pandas dataframe.plot

Grammar of graphics¶

  • Plotnine

Interactive¶

  • Mpld3
  • Plotly
  • Bokeh

Why visualize data at all?¶

Arguments for:

  • Let's people see the data
  • The eye can extract it's own statistics and conclusions
  • Explore the data, guide statistical analysis
  • More impactful/engaging statistical content

Arguments against:

  • Can mislead people without being an outright lie
  • Often is a graphical design exercise / data is not the focus anymore
  • Humans find patterns where there are none

  • https://www.sacbee.com/news/local/transportation/article151302502.html

How to correct this issue?¶

  • add textual context, should alert the reader to the issue of un-observed baseline.
  • more educated data visualization viewers
  • do not overexaggerate conclusions: "where Sacramento bicyclists are hit most often"
  • choose a different visualization / scrap the analysis altogether

Conclusions¶

  • context matters: textual and viewer experience
  • visualization does not overcome statistical issues: multiple testing problems, spurious patterns, etc.

Visualization is only as good as statistics¶

  • hidden multiple tests
  • implied / unreported baselines
  • possible confounding variables

  • http://tylervigen.com/spurious-correlations

Graphical excellence¶

  • shows the data
  • induce the viewer to think about substance rather than methodology
  • avoid distortion of data
  • present many numbers in small space
  • make large datasets coherent
  • encourage the eye to compare different pieces of data
  • reveal the data at several levels of detail
  • serve a reasonably clear purpose: description, exploration, tabulation, or decoration
  • be closely integrated with the statistical and verbal descriptions of a data set

(The Visual Display of Quantitative Info., Tufte)

Deconstructing the plot¶

  1. geometric objects, and aesthetic elements
  2. scales and coordinate systems,
  3. annotation for the plot.

Hubble plot¶

  • the data points and regression lines are all geometric objects
  • the scales and coordinate systems are represented by the guide lines and ticks
  • the annotation is the axis labels.

Elements of Plot¶

  • Geometric objects can be points (as in a scatter plot), lines (as in regression line), or polygons (as in the counties in the chloropleth map).
  • These objects have various aesthetics, such as the position of a point or the width of a line.
  • One plot may have many layers with different layers containing different geometric objects.
  • A scale will map the data to the aesthetics.

http://rhythm-of-food.net/¶

  • Read the instructions (how to read this visualization)
  • To play this game:
    • Look at the visualization
    • Extract conclusions quickly

Common distortions in visualization¶

  • in our scatterplots, the aesthetic mappings to the size of a point geom using radius instead of area to calculate the scale (area does not match the quantity)
  • remove or lower the X-axis from a bar chart which makes the area of the bar appear larger than the actual number that they represent
  • graphics can be distracting and some graphic design elements can detract from the display of information

State-wide obervations for OH 2016¶

  • 8887 Precinct with average 631 voters
  • 50.6% of voters voted for Trump, 42.7% for Hillary
  • 5.6 Mill people voted, 71.3% of registered voters
  • Third party and independent candidates are
    • Gary Johnson: 3.1%
    • Jill Stein: 0.83%
    • Richard Duncan: 0.43%
  • 2.2% of those that vote did not vote for president

Geographic observations¶

  • In precincts with few registered voters, there is a strong tendency to vote Trump
  • In precincts with more registed voters, there is a weaker but noticable tendency to vote Clinton

Does fewer/more registered voters correspond to population density?

It is important to be precise in conclusions: number of registered voters is not the same as the population density.

County level analysis of the election results¶

  • In which counties did people vote for Trump/Clinton?
  • What are the population densities?

County level population conclusions¶

  • Split the data by clinton-trump swing:
    • blue: > 10% swing for Clinton
    • red: > 10% swing for Trump
    • purple: in between
  • Blue counties have average of 371,851 voters
  • Red counties have average of 35,768 voters
  • Blue counties have roughly 10 times the population density of red counties

Other observations:

  • Athens (Ohio University) is very blue and rural (outlier)
  • Northwestern counties are very red and rural (extreme)

def comp_cands(cand1,cand2):
    """Scatter plot comparing candidates"""
    candperc1, candperc2 = cand1 + "_perc", cand2 + "_perc"
    OH.plot(candperc1,candperc2,color='b',s = OH['total_voters']/50,edgecolors='white',kind='scatter')
    plt.xlabel(cand1)
    plt.ylabel(cand2)
    plt.title("The precinct level relationship between vote ratio for candidates")
    plt.show()

## Compute Kendall Tau stats
def cand_tau(cand1,cand2):
    """Kendalls tau between candidates"""
    candperc1, candperc2 = cand1 + "_perc", cand2 + "_perc"
    return stats.kendalltau(OH[candperc1],OH[candperc2])


candidates = OH.columns.values[2:8]
taus = pd.DataFrame(({cand2: cand_tau(cand1,cand2)[0] \
                      for cand2 in candidates} for cand1 in candidates),index=candidates)

Causal effects of voting systems on Clinton-Trump swing?¶

There was serious public concern about the hacking of certain voting system. Particularly, voting systems such as the Accuvote TS are touch screens that runs off of Windows CE and maintain the votes in memory. These have been noted to be vunerable, as could any voting systems where a computer is involved (including optical scanners). I am interested to see if there is evidence in the voting record of widespread hacking.

Does this mean that the election was hacked?¶

  • Percent swing is highly dependent on election system!
  • BUT so is voter density

Final conclusions¶

  1. Election outcome in a county is highly dependent on the voter density (voters/sqr. mile) with more rural areas reliably voting Republican (except Athens county)
  2. Third party candidate votes are weakly associated with the election outcome, with red precincts tending to vote more for Johnson, and blue precincts tending toward Stein.
  3. There is insufficient statistical evidence for a causal effect of voting system on the election outcome.
